"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH4" = "Researchers are still working to fully understand the roles of REM and Deep sleep. Different people tend to get different amounts of each and some don’t experience either on a given night.";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH4" = "There are several tips you can use to give yourself the best chance of getting good sleep. Read more [here]().";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH5" = "A sleep tracking device can help you get the data you need to understand how well you’re doing in each of these areas.";
"INTRO_PARAGRAPH2" = "For doctors and scientists, there are a few key metrics they look at to get an objective sense of your sleep—when you go to sleep, how long you sleep and your sleep stages, how many times you wake up, and your time awake.";
"ARTICLE_DESCRIPTION" = "How to get the sleep you need and why it matters.";
"ARTICLE_TITLE" = "Getting a Sense of How Well You’re Sleeping";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH1" = "The most important element of sleep is how many hours you’re getting. It’s recommended that most adults get at least seven hours on a regular basis, while teenagers are recommended to consistently get eight to ten hours per night. These time ranges give your body and mind the time it needs to rest and restore itself.";
"SECTION2_HEADER" = "Taking a longer view on your sleep";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH1" = "While day-to-day sleep quality is important, your longterm sleep patterns have a much bigger impact on you. If you’re consistently getting the sleep you need, your body is able to repair itself. If you sleep really badly for several nights in a row, you’ll likely notice it physically, because your body hasn’t had a chance to rest and repair. Eventually, it could have longterm consequences for your health.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH2" = "Another key element is the timing of when you go to sleep, sometimes referred to as sleep consistency. Getting to bed around the same time each night can help you fall asleep more easily, meet your sleep duration goals, and improve the overall quality of your sleep.";
"INTRO_PARAGRAPH3" = "Your body and mind need time to rest and restore themselves while you’re sleeping. And these metrics can give you a sense of how well you’re sleeping over time, which can have a lasting effect on your overall health.";
"SECTION1_HEADER" = "Understanding the Metrics";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH2" = "Something to avoid is worrying about your sleep night after night. Instead, try to focus on the longterm trends, keeping a consistent bedtime, and meeting your sleep duration goals. If you’re struggling, talk with your doctor or care team about ways you can support your sleep.";
"SECTION1_PARAGRAPH3" = "How often you wake up, how long it takes you to get back to sleep, and your sleep stages can also have an impact. Many researchers believe Core sleep is important for memory and this stage is typically most of your sleep. Dreaming often happens during REM sleep. And in Deep sleep, your brain activity is slow and this is often when the body works to repair itself.";
"INTRO_PARAGRAPH1" = "Sleep is unique from person to person. Two people might get the exact same sleep and wake up feeling completely different. How you feel that day is an important marker of your sleep quality on a day-to-day basis.";
"VIEW_TITLE" = "Sleep Article";
"SECTION2_PARAGRAPH3" = "If you have a bedtime that has to shift significantly during the week—maybe you’re a new parent, you’re traveling, or you work nights—it can have an impact on the measured quality of your sleep.";
